25    /**
26    * Builder object that can be used for per-serialization configuration of
27    * deserialization parameters, such as root type to use or object
28    * to update (instead of constructing new instance).
29    *<p>
30    * Uses "fluent" (or, kind of, builder) pattern so that instances are immutable
31    * (and thus fully thread-safe with no external synchronization);
32    * new instances are constructed for different configurations.
33    * Instances are initially constructed by {@link ObjectMapper} and can be
34    * reused, shared, cached; both because of thread-safety and because
35    * instances are relatively light-weight.
36    */

989    /**
990    * Method for reading sequence of Objects from parser stream.
991    *<p>
992    * Sequence can be either wrapped or unwrapped root-level sequence:
993    * wrapped means that the elements are enclosed in JSON Array;
994    * and unwrapped that elements are directly accessed at main level.
995    * Assumption is that iff the first token of the document is
996    * <code>START_ARRAY</code>, we have a wrapped sequence; otherwise
997    * unwrapped. For wrapped sequences, leading <code>START_ARRAY</code>
998    * is skipped, so that for both cases, underlying {@link JsonParser}
999    * will point to what is expected to be the first token of the first
1000    * element.
1001    *<p>
1002    * Note that the wrapped vs unwrapped logic means that it is NOT
1003    * possible to use this method for reading an unwrapped sequence
1004    * of elements written as JSON Arrays: to read such sequences, one
1005    * has to use {@link #readValues(JsonParser)}, making sure parser
1006    * points to the first token of the first element (i.e. the second
1007    * <code>START_ARRAY</code> which is part of the first element).
1008    */
